observations.recommendation:
We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor to enjoin the following:
Property/ Supply Officer/ Municipal Treasurer:
For the Municipal Treasurer to turn over to the designated Supply Officer the last Report on Inventory Count/ RPCPPE conducted by its office, including all PARs/AREs of PPEs;
For the designated Supply Officer to update/ renew all the PARs/ AREs issued to end-users, and identify the properties issued to retired/ resigned employees/ officials that were not properly turned over. This would facilitate the identification of PPEs that are missing or not found in the supposed station, and update the RPCPPE through the conduct of a physical inventory of assets, ensuring to include all new acquisitions of PPEs and those assets that are not yet counted in the report;
Municipal Accountant:
To provide updated PPE Ledger Cards (PPELCs) to the Inventory Committee, including all newly acquired assets;
After the conclusion of activities for One-Time Cleansing, provide for the accounting entries for the recognition of PPEs found at the station but not previously recorded, recognition of loss of PPEs, writing-off/ dropping from the books of accounts the remaining balances/ amounts lumped under the unreconciled SL of PPEs, and derecognition of non-existing/ missing PPEs (accomplish Annex D and also refer to Annex E of COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the entries)
Provide disclosures on PPE in the Notes to FS the total amount of non-existing/ missing PPEs included in the PPE balance, supported with breakdown as to sub-major PPE account group, and PPEs found at the station which are still needing appraisal, following item 9.0 of the same COA Circular;
Inventory Committee members:
To create a strategic Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) detailing the specific assignments /duties of the committee members, cut-off dates, and schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities to be approved by the Municipal Mayor;
To prepare the PIP based on the latest RPCPPE or Inventory Count Form (Annex A) and PPELCs, as coordinated with the Property Unit/ designated Supply Officer and Accounting Unit;
If no RPCPPE was accomplished, prepare the format for Inventory Count Form (ICF) following Annex A, and instruct all offices to provide list of PPEs assigned/ detailed at their stations; and ensure that the inventory taking activities are executed according to the approved PIP; the condition of the PPEs counted shall be clearly indicated in the ICF;
For PPEs that are reported missing/non-existent, not found in the station, or counted but not yet recorded, follow through with the procedures as enumerated under COA Circular 2020-006; and
With the cooperation of the designated Supply Officer, accomplish Annexes A, B, and C of the same COA Circular.
Lastly, Disposal Committee shall be created pursuant to COA-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 2024-1, dated January 30, 2024. This committee shall effect the disposal of PPEs as a result of the One-Time Cleansing of accounts.

We have recommended the Municipal Mayor to enjoin the Treasury office the following:
For all collecting officers to remit their collections and accomplish their Report of Collections and Deposits (RCD) at close of each business day and see to it that no accumulation of cash from collections and mingling of funds shall be made by any collector to avoid loss, misapplication and/or unauthorized use;
To ensure that all collections are deposited intact and daily, or on the next banking day;
To ensure that RCDs and Summary of Collections are submitted to the Accounting Unit daily;
To instruct the Liquidating Officer to verify the actual amounts of collections remitted by each collecting officer;
 To regularly update the cashbooks on the amount of collections and deposits made for the day;
To engage in computerized system of issuing ORs to minimize human errors in recording collections and improve overall procedural flow of the transactions;
Liquidation for the unused portion of CAs should be made through issuance of ORs; and
should there be any cash overage incurred, demand written explanation from the Accountable Officer concerned. If no satisfactory explanation was provided, issue OR for the amount of overage in favor of the government. In case of cash shortage, demand immediately the payment of the amount of shortage.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the following personnel to take appropriate actions aimed at enhancing the efficiency of tax collection:
1.  Market Supervisor, as well as the members of Market Committee, to develop and implement effective strategies to ensure the regular collection of monthly stall rentals and strictly enforce penalties for late or non-payment. Although the lease term may extend up to five years, there must be at least quarterly monitoring of stall occupancy to verify whether stallholders remain compliant with the provisions of Section 7A.10 of the Revised Revenue Code; also, maintain updated stallholder records, which include contract terms, payment history, and assigned stall location. Flag stall accounts with repeated delinquencies or violations;
2. The Municipal Treasurer:
To issue demand letters to the delinquencies of identified market stallholders. Remind them that non-payment thereof would permanently disqualify them on the granting of market stall lease contract of the new market; also, revoke the current/ existing lease contract and offer the stalls to other vendors;
Intensify tax campaigns. Tax campaigns should include educating constituents on the importance of RPTs, available amnesty programs, and discounts for paying early. If possible, involve the Barangay officials for the widest information dissemination, especially those barangays with highest amount of RPT delinquencies;
Issue Notices of Delinquency to all delinquent taxpayers and post the same at the Municipal Hall at conspicuous places in each barangay; and
Avail remedies in collecting delinquent RPTs provided under RA No. 7160, which includes the sale or auction of the property or a usable portion thereof as may be necessary to satisfy the tax delinquency and expenses of sale.

We have recommended the Municipal Mayor to instruct the Inventory Committee and key personnel concerned to:

Complete the conduct of annual physical inventory and make updates on the current/ existing inventory reports, and to adhere with the timeline of activities under the Physical Inventory Plan (PIP). The Inventory Committee and accounting shall compare the latest Report on the RPCPPE/Inventory Report with the PPE Ledger Cards (PPELCs); 

The Inventory Committee shall prepare a list of PPE items which are recorded in the PPELCs but not included in the RPCPPE/Physical Inventory Report as well as PPE items which are included in the RPCPPE but not recorded in the PPELCs;

After the completion of physical count, for the PPEs classified as non-existing/ missing and of those without available records of accountability, the Management should conduct the procedures enumerated under Items 7 and 8 of the same COA Circular for the disposition and derecognition.

